column1: ... = data not available; I = marks break in series;  0.0 = magnitude is less than half of unit employed; * = provisional, preliminary, estimate, budget figure; $ = United States dollars; ₹ = Indian rupees; cif = cost, insurance, and freight; fob = free on board; GDP = gross domestic product; GNI = gross national income; IMF = International Monetary Fund; km2 = square kilometer; kWh = kilowatt-hour; L = liter; m3 = cubic meters; NPISHs = nonprofit institutions serving households; SDRs = special drawing rights; t = metric ton.

Note: A base year represented as, e.g., 2014/2015, corresponds to the fiscal year (e.g., beginning 1 April 2014 and ending 31 March 2015) and related data are presented in the column for the single year during which most of the fiscal year occurred (e.g., 2014) .

column2: For 2000–2010, data were estimated based on GDP per capita figures from the Government of India's Central Statistics Office. For 2011 onward, data are from Central Statistics Office national accounts press notes.
For 2000, 2005, 2009, and 2011, data on labor force are estimates from the National Sample Survey, and are based on total population.
For 2011 onward, there are changes in basic concepts in line with the changing of the base year to 2011/2012 and the adoption of the System of National Accounts 2008.
For 2011–2017, refers to communication and services related to broadcasting.
For 2000–2010, data include real estate, ownership of dwelling, and professional services.
Refers to gross capital formation, which refers to the sum of gross fixed capital formation, valuables, increases in stocks, and errors and omissions.
Annual growth of GDP refers to market prices, and growth per sector at basic prices.
Midyear population estimates per fiscal year (i.e., 1 October) were used for deriving per capita figures.
For the fiscal year beginning 1 April.
Data refer to availability for consumption.
Data refer to availability for consumption excluding imported liquefied natural gas.
For 2000–2005, data include electricity consumed in auxiliary stations and losses in transmission and distribution system. For 2008–2014, data include thermal, hydropower, and nuclear energy.
Gasoline premium refers to motor spirit; diesel refers to high-speed diesel oil.
Prior to 2011, data refer to CPI for industrial workers. From 2011 onward, data refer to the new CPI series (national combining rural and urban).
Refers to pan, tobacco, and intoxicants.
For 2000–2005, data refer to calendar year averages. Prior to 2011, data refer to CPI for industrial workers.
Refers to currency with the public, defined as currency in circulation less cash in hand with banks.
Refers to deposit money of the public, defined as deposit money with banks and other deposits with the Reserve Bank of India (RBI); excludes government deposits.
Quasi-money refers to broad money (M3) less narrow money (M1), which is equal to time deposits.

For 2004, data are adjusted based on the mergers and conversion in the banking system. For 2005, data are not comparable with those of the other years as 2005 data include 27 fortnights, versus the usual 26 fortnights.
Residual item; defined as government's currency liabilities to the public less banking sector's net nonmonetary liabilities other than time deposits.
Data refer to bank credits of commercial banks.
Prior to 2002, data refer to commercial and state cooperative banks. From 2002 onward, data refer to total bank credit of commercial banks.
Refers to preshipment export credit up to 180 days.
Refers to ceiling rates on general credit prescribed by the RBI. Data from 2000 refer to postshipment export credit of usance bills up to 90 days.

Disinvestment receipts and total capital receipts of 2007-2008 include an amount of ₹343.09 billion under miscellaneous capital receipts, which represents the RBI's surplus transferred to the central government on account of the transfer of its stake in the State Bank of India to the central government. Further, data exclude borrowings and other liabilities.
Data refers to financing gross fiscal deficit market and other borrowings.
For 2000–2009, follows the IMF's Balance of Payments Manual (fifth edition). For 2010 onward, follow's the IMF's Balance of Payments and International Investment Position Manual (sixth edition).
Total may not add up due to other components not included in the data presentation, i.e., external assistance, commercial borrowings, short terms credit, and debt service.
